What is an Array?

An array stores multiple values in a single variable.

Instead of:

let student1 = "Priya";
let student2 = "Lokesh";
let student3 = "Kumar";

Use:

let students = ["Priya", "Lokesh", "Kumar"];
Creating Arrays
Method 1 (Recommended)
let fruits = ["Apple", "Banana", "Orange"];
Method 2
let numbers = [10, 20, 30, 40];
Mixed Data Types
let data = [
    "Priya",
    27,
    true,
    null
];

Although possible, it's better to keep similar types together.

Array Index

Array indexes start from 0.

Apple     Banana     Orange

  0          1          2
Accessing Elements
let fruits = ["Apple", "Banana", "Orange"];

console.log(fruits[0]);
console.log(fruits[1]);
console.log(fruits[2]);

Output

Apple
Banana
Orange
Array Length
let fruits = ["Apple", "Banana", "Orange"];

console.log(fruits.length);

Output

3
Modify an Element
let fruits = ["Apple", "Banana", "Orange"];

fruits[1] = "Mango";

console.log(fruits);

Output

["Apple", "Mango", "Orange"]
1. push() ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

Adds elements to the end of an array.

let fruits = ["Apple", "Banana"];

fruits.push("Orange");

console.log(fruits);

Output

["Apple", "Banana", "Orange"]
Add Multiple Elements
fruits.push("Grapes", "Mango");

Output

["Apple", "Banana", "Orange", "Grapes", "Mango"]
2. pop() ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

Removes the last element.

let fruits = ["Apple", "Banana", "Orange"];

fruits.pop();

console.log(fruits);

Output

["Apple", "Banana"]
Store Removed Element
let fruits = ["Apple", "Banana", "Orange"];

let removed = fruits.pop();

console.log(removed);

Output

Orange
3. shift() ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

Removes the first element.

let fruits = ["Apple", "Banana", "Orange"];

fruits.shift();

console.log(fruits);

Output

["Banana", "Orange"]
4. unshift() ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

Adds elements to the beginning.

let fruits = ["Banana", "Orange"];

fruits.unshift("Apple");

console.log(fruits);

Output

["Apple", "Banana", "Orange"]
5. splice() ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

splice() is one of the most important array methods.

It can:

Remove elements
Add elements
Replace elements
Syntax
array.splice(startIndex, deleteCount, item1, item2, ...);
Remove Elements
let fruits = ["Apple", "Banana", "Orange"];

fruits.splice(1, 1);

console.log(fruits);

Output

["Apple", "Orange"]
Add Elements
let fruits = ["Apple", "Orange"];

fruits.splice(1, 0, "Banana");

console.log(fruits);

Output

["Apple", "Banana", "Orange"]
Replace Elements
let fruits = ["Apple", "Banana", "Orange"];

fruits.splice(1, 1, "Mango");

console.log(fruits);

Output

["Apple", "Mango", "Orange"]
6. slice() ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

Returns a portion of an array without modifying the original.

let fruits = ["Apple", "Banana", "Orange", "Mango"];

let result = fruits.slice(1, 3);

console.log(result);

Output

["Banana", "Orange"]

Original array remains unchanged.

Difference Between splice() and slice()
splice()	slice()
Modifies the original array	Does not modify the original
Can add, remove, replace	Only copies a portion
Returns removed elements	Returns a new array
Loop Through an Array
Using for
let fruits = ["Apple", "Banana", "Orange"];

for (let i = 0; i < fruits.length; i++) {
    console.log(fruits[i]);
}
Using for...of
let fruits = ["Apple", "Banana", "Orange"];

for (let fruit of fruits) {
    console.log(fruit);
}

Output

Apple
Banana
Orange

Interview Questions ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐
1. What is an array?

An array is a data structure used to store multiple values in a single variable.

2. Difference between push() and unshift()?
push() adds elements to the end.
unshift() adds elements to the beginning.
3. Difference between pop() and shift()?
pop() removes the last element.
shift() removes the first element.
4. Difference between slice() and splice()?
slice() creates a copy of part of an array without changing the original.
splice() changes the original array by adding, removing, or replacing elements.
